<DOC><DOCNO> AP890616-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0434EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Secord-DrunkenDriving     06-16 0271</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Secord-Drunken Driving,260</SECOND><HEAD>Iran-Contra Figure Again Charged With Drunken Driving</HEAD><DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iran-Contra figure Richard Secord faces a newcharge of drunken driving, authorities in this Washington, D.C.,suburb said.   Secord is appealing a conviction last month for the same offense.   The 56-year-old retired Air Force major general was arrested inthe town of Vienna early Wednesday morning, according to MarieKisner, public information officer for the town.   She said the arrest occurred after a police officer spotted asuspicious looking vehicle that was moving very slowly and came toalmost a complete stop at a green light.   Secord, cited for drunken driving and refusing to give a breathor blood sample, was released on $750 cash bond after spendingseveral hours in the Fairfax County jail, Kisner said.   He was convicted May 11 in Fairfax County of driving with analcohol level of 0.20, twice the legal limit in Virginia.   District Judge Barbara Kimble sentenced him to 30 days in jail,suspended his driver's license for six months, fined $500 andordered to enroll in an Alcohol Safety Awareness program. Kimblethen suspended the jail time and $200 of the fine and allowed Secordto drive his car to work and to the alcohol program.   Secord filed an appeal and a new trial is scheduled for Aug. 24.   Secord was a key figure who worked with former White House aideOliver L. North in the Iran-Contra affair. He is charged with payingillegal gratuities to North during the period when the Reaganadministration was covertly selling arms to Iran and with perjuringhimself in testimony to Congress.</TEXT></DOC>